{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539474"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:41:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:41:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16618"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16618"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.11,0.6,0.04,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9309"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89889"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9309"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16618"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74058"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"8929"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22070"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30615"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35643"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45693"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89889","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89889"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with severe chest tightness, coughing, and shortness of breath. The symptoms began six hours ago while he was attempting to extract gold from dental amalgam in his garage using heat. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He works as a jeweller.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 145/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 89% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. He has widespread wheeze and crackles on chest auscultation. A chest X-ray shows diffuse bilateral infiltrates.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral penicillamine","Intravenous N-acetylcysteine","Intravenous dimercaprol","Oral penicillin","Oral succimer"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute mercury vapour toxicity after heating dental amalgam, which contains approximately 50% elemental mercury. When heated, mercury vaporises and can be inhaled, leading to acute lung injury and pneumonitis. The primary effects of acute mercury vapour exposure are respiratory, though systemic absorption can also occur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous dimercaprol\u003C/strong\u003E (British Anti-Lewisite, BAL) is the chelating agent of choice for acute mercury toxicity. It is administered parenterally and is particularly effective for treating toxicity from mercury, lead, arsenic, and gold. It should be administered as soon as possible after exposure, along with supportive care including oxygen therapy and monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral succimer\u003C/strong\u003E (DMSA) is an alternative chelating agent that can be used for mercury poisoning, but it is more commonly used for chronic exposure or as follow-up therapy after initial treatment with dimercaprol. It is not the first-line treatment for acute exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral penicillamine\u003C/strong\u003E is another chelating agent that can be used for heavy metal poisoning, particularly for copper and lead, but it is not the first-line treatment for acute mercury toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous N-acetylcysteine\u003C/strong\u003E is used primarily for acetaminophen overdose and as a mucolytic agent. It does not have a role in treating mercury toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral penicillin\u003C/strong\u003E would not be helpful in this case as the patient\u0027s symptoms are due to direct chemical injury from mercury vapour rather than infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevention of mercury exposure through proper occupational safety measures is crucial. Dental amalgam should never be heated without proper ventilation and safety equipment, as mercury vapour can be extremely toxic.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute mercury vapour exposure primarily affects the respiratory system causing pneumonitis and respiratory distress.","Dimercaprol (BAL) is the parenteral chelating agent for acute mercury toxicity.","Chronic mercury exposure classically causes tremor, personality changes, and gingivitis.","Chelation therapy with dimercaprol is the primary treatment for acute mercury toxicity."],"references":["Long N, Long N. Mercury toxicity [Internet]. Life in the Fast Lane \u2022 LITFL. 2019. Available at: https://litfl.com/mercury-toxicity/\u200c","Dimercaprol (British Anti-Lewisite [BAL]). Queensland Government. Queensland Poisons Information Centre. [cited 2025 Mar 11] Available at: https://www.poisonsinfo.health.qld.gov.au/for-health-professionals/antidote-stocking-recommendations/dimercaprol-british-anti-lewisite-bal"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74058"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16618"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74058"},"attributes":{"c